Regarding HTML code examples, I can provide you with some code snippets and example structures that might be useful for teaching sensitive data handling. Here are a few examples:

**Example 1: Masked SSN Input**

```html
<input type="text" id="ssn" name="ssn" placeholder="XXX-XX-XXXX" pattern="[0-9]{3}-[0-9]{2}-[0-9]{4}" title="Enter your Social Security Number in the format XXX-XX-XXXX">
```

This example uses a `pattern` attribute to enforce a specific format for the SSN, and a `placeholder` attribute to provide guidance on the expected format.

**Example 2: Redacted SSN Input**

```html
<input type="text" id="ssn" name="ssn" value="XXXX-XX-XXXX" readonly>
```

This example uses a `value` attribute to set the initial value of the input field to a redacted SSN, and a `readonly` attribute to prevent the user from editing the value.

**Example 3: Secure SSN Input with JavaScript**

```html
<input type="text" id="ssn" name="ssn" placeholder="XXX-XX-XXXX">
<script>
  const ssnInput = document.getElementById('ssn');
  ssnInput.addEventListener('input', (e) => {
    const value = e.target.value;
    const maskedValue = value.replace(/\d/g, '*');
    e.target.value = maskedValue;
  });
</script>
```

This example uses JavaScript to mask the SSN input field as the user types, replacing each digit with an asterisk (\*) to prevent sensitive information from being visible.

**Example 4: SSN Validation with JavaScript**

```html
<input type="text" id="ssn" name="ssn" placeholder="XXX-XX-XXXX">
<script>
  const ssnInput = document.getElementById('ssn');
  ssnInput.addEventListener('input', (e) => {
    const value = e.target.value;
    const pattern = /^[0-9]{3}-[0-9]{2}-[0-9]{4}$/;
    if (!pattern.test(value)) {
      alert('Invalid Social Security Number format. Please enter XXX-XX-XXXX.');
    }
  });
</script>
```

This example uses JavaScript to validate the SSN input field as the user types, checking if the value matches the expected format (XXX-XX-XXXX).

These code snippets and example structures can be used as teaching tools to demonstrate best practices for sensitive data handling, including masking, redaction, and validation.

Here's a comprehensive example form structure for handling Social Security numbers, incorporating best practices for naming conventions, masking, and validation:

**Form Structure:**

```html
<form id="ssn-form">
  <h2>SSN Form</h2>
  <label for="ssn">Social Security Number:</label>
  <input type="text" id="ssn" name="ssn" placeholder="XXX-XX-XXXX" pattern="[0-9]{3}-[0-9]{2}-[0-9]{4}" title="Enter your Social Security Number in the format XXX-XX-XXXX">
  <div id="ssn-error" class="error-message"></div>
  <button type="submit">Submit</button>
</form>
```

**JavaScript Code:**

```javascript
const ssnForm = document.getElementById('ssn-form');
const ssnInput = document.getElementById('ssn');
const ssnError = document.getElementById('ssn-error');

ssnForm.addEventListener('submit', (e) => {
  e.preventDefault();
  const value = ssnInput.value;
  const pattern = /^[0-9]{3}-[0-9]{2}-[0-9]{4}$/;
  if (!pattern.test(value)) {
    ssnError.textContent = 'Invalid Social Security Number format. Please enter XXX-XX-XXXX.';
    ssnError.style.display = 'block';
  } else {
    // Mask the SSN input field
    const maskedValue = value.replace(/\d/g, '*');
    ssnInput.value = maskedValue;
    ssnError.style.display = 'none';
  }
});

ssnInput.addEventListener('input', (e) => {
  const value = e.target.value;
  const pattern = /^[0-9]{3}-[0-9]{2}-[0-9]{4}$/;
  if (!pattern.test(value)) {
    ssnError.textContent = 'Invalid Social Security Number format. Please enter XXX-XX-XXXX.';
    ssnError.style.display = 'block';
  } else {
    ssnError.style.display = 'none';
  }
});
```

**CSS Code:**

```css
.error-message {
  display: none;
  color: red;
}

.error-message.show {
  display: block;
}
```

